        <h2 class="py-4 italic font-semibold">Apps don’t matter. People do.</h2>

        <p class="py-4">Yes, we built Landscape, but we’re not the only ones making apps. We designed our suite of apps to be as simple and flexible as possible so people can make it theirs.</p>
        <p class="py-4">Because all apps on Landscape have one login and can push and pull data from one another, it’s easy to tailor your digital toolkit to fit your preferences. If you want to replace Groups and Talk, feel free to build better, more featureful versions, or extensions or compliments to them—all using the same data.</p>
        <p class="py-4">Our apps are almost besides the point. It’s the people and how they use our tools that count.</p>
        <p class="py-4">For example, let’s say your friend or colleague comes up with a better messenger app they built on top of our Talk app, or a remix of our Notebook app more tailored to your group’s writing needs. You can switch to using those apps without losing any of the conversations or work you had in Talk and Notebook. It’s kind of like being able to edit the same set of documents on Roam, Google Docs and Notion, or messaging your friends on Telegram from Signal.</p>
        <p class="py-4">Heed is a great example of our community taking advantage of Landscape’s open-source foundation. ~sogrum-savluc made an app that reorganizes your Gallery channels into a single feed you can browse and comment on, just like Instagram. Would Tlon personally prefer to leave Instagram behind for something more clutter-free like Groups? Yes. Do we think that’s the only way to present media on Landscape? Definitely not. ~sogrum-savluc saw a way to personalize the Landscape user experience and, pulling data from the Groups app, made it happen.</p>
        <p class="py-4">Similarly, but in a totally different style, ~paldev’s s'core is a leaderboard app that pulls data from the groups you're in.</p>
        <p class="py-4">Not only are apps easy to extend on Landscape. They’re easy to ship and scale. That’s because Landscape isn’t just a collection of apps. It’s a distribution system for apps.</p>
        <p class="py-4">The coolest, most freeing thing about this app distribution system? Because each user on Landscape runs their own software and custodies their own data, developers get to skip the hurdle of how to keep their apps running, where to store that data and what to do with it. Instead, they get to jump right into the meat of the app.</p>
        <p class="py-4">Typically when building an app, a developer has a ton of upfront costs. They’ve got to decide what stack to use and set it up. They’ve got to build a system for authentication. They’ve got to decide how they’re going to handle user details, store data and process data. They’ve got to decide how they’re going to keep it online.</p>
        <p class="py-4">And that’s just to get it started. If the app blows up, their server bills are going to get really expensive. Developers are used to this, and it’s why you might see so many people raising money before they even start to build. It’s also why you see some developers sell off their apps as soon as they gain momentum (see Wordle). Packy unpacks this nicely <a href="https://www.notboring.co/p/small-applications-growing-protocols">here</a>.</p>
        <p class="py-4">On Landscape, you don’t deal with authentication because everyone has a single login for everything. They’re logged in before they even install your app. Neither do you have to store user data because each user stores their own data. You just write the core of the app, save it to Urbit’s file system, and wait for your friends to download it from that location. No upfront costs but your time—and we aim to consume as little of that as possible.</p>
        <p class="py-4">This means that Landscape is a place where a whole universe of small apps can take off without the pressure to monetize, grow and force some hockey stick-shaped graph. Landscape apps can just be useful, fun and productive.</p>
        <p class="py-4">Eventually, they should also make money, and just as easily as they take to build. We haven’t gotten to payments quite yet—but we look forward to developers being directly compensated for building things. No app store, no problem. When everyone has an Urbit ID it’s easy to build a reputation system for app devs.</p>
        
